Tutorial:   Installing Jupyter (Windows 10)



⚠️ Many university computers already have Jupyter installed. If you are using a university computer, check whether Jupyter is installed by entering `jupyter` in the Windows search bar.



The easiest way to install Jupyter is to install Anaconda.

Below are step-by-step instructions for (a) installing Anaconda, then (b) checking the Jupyter installation.

Table of Contents¶

  • Step 1:   Check Windows version
  • Step 2:   Install Anaconda
  • Step 3:   Check Jupyter installation

Step 1:   Check Windows version   (64 bit or 32 bit)

Back to Table of Contents

  1. In the Windows search bar, enter about , then select About your PC.





  1. In the About window, find System type, and note whether the type is 64 bit or 32 bit.



In this case, the type is 64 bit





Step 2:   Install Anaconda

Back to Table of Contents

  1. Go to anaconda.com/distribution , and select Windows





  1. Scroll down to the Windows Installer options, and download the Python 3.7 version.

⚠️ Choose either 64 bit or 32 bit     (see Step 1)





  1. Open the installer and install the software. Detailed installation instructions: (English) (日本語) (日本語２)





Step 3:   Check Jupyter installation

Back to Table of Contents



  1. Enter jupyter notebook in the Windows search bar, then select the Jupyter Notebook app.





  1. If you have multiple browsers, Windows may ask you which browser you want to use. Choose any browser (e.g. Firefox, Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, etc.)





  1. When the Jupyter home page launches, select New, then select a Python 3 Notebook.





  1. When the notebook launches, enter print( "Hello world!" ) in the cell, then select Run.





  1. Verify that Hello world! is printed as output.





Congratulations!¶

Jupyter is now installed and ready to go.
